3","1275–Female":"1275–Overleden","1304":"1304","1324":"1324","18 October 1361":"18 oktober 1361","1368":"1368","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","16 Jun 1363":"16 juni 1363","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","Hempnall, Norfolk, England":"Hempnall, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Pennington, Lancashire, England":"Pennington, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dunmow, Essex, England":"Dunmow, Essex, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Preston Richard, Heversham, Westmoreland, England":"Preston Richard, Westmorland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Woodham Walton, Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"en":{"1300–1368":"1300–1368","1304–1363":"1304–1363","1324–1361":"1324–1361","1330–1368":"1330–1368","1275–1323":"1275–1323","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1304":"1304","1324":"1324","18 October 1361":"18 October 1361","1368":"1368","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","16 Jun 1363":"16 June 1363","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","Hempnall, Norfolk, England":"Hempnall, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Pennington, Lancashire, England":"Pennington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Dunmow, Essex, England":"Dunmow, Essex, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Preston Richard, Heversham, Westmoreland, England":"Preston Richard, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Woodham Walton, Essex, England":"Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pennington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire and Cumbria):","habitational name from Pennington in Furness (Lancashire), which derives from Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, or from Pennington in Leigh (Lancashire), which probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Pinna</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","habitational name from Pennington (Hampshire), or from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hampshire); see   Penton  . All have the same etymology as Pennington in Furness; see 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Penington","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Pennington  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland.","History: Edward Penington, born in 1667 in Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England, was appointed surveyor-general of the province of PA in 1698 and accompanied William Penn to Philadelphia."]},{"name":"Penton","meanings":["English (mainly Hampshire):","habitational name from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hanmpshire), or from a shortened form of   Pennington   2. The placenames denoted a farm or estate for which a penny tax was payable (Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i>).","in north-west England, a shortened form of   Pennington   1, from either of the places called Pennington in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When 8 John Pennington was born in 1300, in Pennington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Pennington, was 25 and his mother, Mother Pennington, was 25. He married Joan (De Multon) Pennington in 1330, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1368, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1300–1368":"1300–1368","1304–1363":"1304–1363","1324–1361":"1324–1361","1330–1368":"1330–1368","1275–1323":"1275–1323","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1304":"1304","1324":"1324","18 October 1361":"18. oktoober 1361","1368":"1368","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","16 Jun 1363":"16. juuni 1363","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","Hempnall, Norfolk, England":"Hempnall, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pennington, Lancashire, England":"Pennington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dunmow, Essex, England":"Dunmow, Essex, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Preston Richard, Heversham, Westmoreland, England":"Preston Richard, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Woodham Walton, Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fi":{"1300–1368":"1300–1368","1304–1363":"1304–1363","1324–1361":"1324–1361","1330–1368":"1330–1368","1275–1323":"1275–1323","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1304":"1304","1324":"1324","18 October 1361":"18. lokakuuta 1361","1368":"1368","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","16 Jun 1363":"16. kesäkuuta 1363","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","Hempnall, Norfolk, England":"Hempnall, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt 